**PATENT CLAIMS**

1.  A single-molecule tracking system comprising:  
    a. a plurality of single-molecule imaging sensors configured to acquire time-series fluorescence data from labeled biomolecules;  
    b. a graph neural network (GNN) processor operatively coupled to the imaging sensors, wherein the GNN processor constructs a dynamic molecular interaction graph from the time-series fluorescence data by:  
        i. extracting spatial coordinates of individual fluorophore emissions across sequential frames;  
        ii. generating node embeddings representing each fluorophore emission event;  
        iii. propagating message-passing updates across graph edges to model transient molecular interactions;  
        iv. outputting node-level predictions of molecular trajectories;  
    c. a trajectory reconstruction module configured to assemble the molecular trajectories from the GNN outputs;  
    d. wherein the GNN processor is trained using a loss function comprising a weighted combination of a trajectory consistency loss and a spatial coherence regularization term, wherein the weights are determined via Bayesian optimization to minimize false-positive tracking events in dense cellular environments;  
    e. wherein the system operates in real time to update molecular trajectories at a frame rate of at least 50 Hz without external user intervention.

2.  The system of claim 1, wherein the graph neural network comprises:  
    a. a message-passing layer implementing a gated graph convolution with learnable edge weights;  
    b. a node feature encoder comprising a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) that processes fluorophore intensity, photobleaching kinetics, and localization uncertainty;  
    c. a readout layer that aggregates node embeddings to generate trajectory probability distributions;  
    wherein the message-passing layer operates on an adjacency matrix derived from Delaunay triangulation of fluorophore localizations.

3.  The system of claim 1, wherein the spatial coherence regularization term penalizes trajectory deviations exceeding a context-dependent angular threshold determined from local cytoskeletal structures identified via co-stained imaging channels.

4.  The system of claim 1, wherein the training data comprises:  
    a. synthetic single-molecule trajectories generated from a reaction-diffusion simulator with known ground-truth interaction topologies;  
    b. experimental data from fixed-cell imaging with ground-truth lineage labels obtained via single-particle tracking (SPT) with gold-standard fiducials;  
    wherein the synthetic and experimental datasets are combined using a curriculum learning schedule that progressively increases complexity.

5.  The system of claim 1, wherein the real-time analysis pipeline integrates with a high-throughput microscopy platform to enable closed-loop feedback control of illumination intensity and exposure duration based on estimated molecular density maps.

6.  The system of claim 1, wherein the graph neural network is configured to generalize across cell types by incorporating cell-type-specific embedding vectors derived from prior training on a meta-dataset of 12 distinct cellular environments.

7.  The system of claim 1, wherein the trajectory reconstruction module employs a Viterbi decoder with transition probabilities learned from the GNN outputs to resolve ambiguous branching events in crowded cellular regions.

8.  The system of claim 1, wherein the loss function includes a term that enforces temporal smoothness of trajectory velocities, wherein the smoothness penalty is scaled by the inverse of the local frame signal-to-noise ratio.

9.  The system of claim 1, wherein the GNN processor is implemented on a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) with pipelined inference stages to achieve sub-10ms latency per frame.

10.  The system of claim 1, wherein the method further comprises:  
    a. receiving a query molecular region of interest from a user interface;  
    b. dynamically reweighting the message-passing update rules to prioritize subgraph nodes within a 3σ radius of the query region;  
    c. outputting enhanced trajectory predictions for the region of interest with increased spatial resolution.

11.  The system of claim 1, wherein the graph neural network architecture is defined by a fixed sequence of message-passing iterations comprising exactly three message exchanges per inference step, wherein the number of iterations is not adjustable during inference.

12.  The system of claim 1, wherein the trajectory predictions include uncertainty quantification via Monte Carlo dropout sampling across GNN layers, wherein the uncertainty is visualized as confidence heatmaps overlaid on the reconstructed trajectories.

13.  The system of claim 1, wherein the method is executed without requiring manual annotation of training data beyond initial fluorophore labeling, wherein the system autonomously identifies and excludes photobleached or outlier emissions via an automated outlier rejection module based on emission lifetime distributions.

14.  The system of claim 1, wherein the real-time analysis pipeline is configured to trigger an alarm event when the estimated molecular interaction density exceeds a threshold derived from historical baseline distributions of the same cellular region.

